Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The existing literature, including the provided references, has begun to explore how language models process semantic phenomena such as animacy (Paper 2), figurative language (Paper 1), and analogical reasoning (Paper 3). However, a critical gap remains in understanding *how* increasing model scale—specifically parameter count and training data volume—affects the emergence of nuanced semantic representations. While Paper 2 shows that models can adapt to atypical animacy (e.g., "a peanut in love"), it does not systematically investigate whether this capacity scales with model size or emerges only beyond certain thresholds. My intuition is that atypical animacy processing serves as a powerful diagnostic probe because it requires models to override default lexical-semantic expectations (e.g., peanuts are inanimate) based on contextual cues (e.g., emotional verbs like "love"). This demands sophisticated integration of syntax, semantics, and world knowledge—capabilities hypothesized to emerge only in larger models. By treating atypical animacy as a behavioral marker for representational depth, we can uncover scaling laws not just in performance but in *semantic flexibility*. This idea differs from prior work by explicitly linking model scale to dynamic semantic adaptation, rather than static classification accuracy. It also introduces controlled syntactic-semantic perturbations to isolate representational shifts, going beyond simple probing tasks.

